---
import BaseLayout from '../../../layouts/BaseLayout.astro';
---
<BaseLayout title="Immigration statistics by country: 20-nation official data comparison | Immigration Factbook" lang="en" altHref="/faq/immigration-statistics-comparison/" description="Compare immigration's fiscal, employment, education and crime impact across 20 Western countries using official primary data from national statistics offices, ministries of finance, and OECD.">
<main class="theme-page">
  <div class="page-header">
    <nav class="breadcrumb"><a href="/en/">Immigration Factbook</a> › <span>FAQ</span></nav>
    <h1>Immigration statistics by country: 20-nation official data comparison</h1>
    <p class="intro">Immigration Factbook compares the fiscal, employment, education and crime impact of immigration across 20 Western countries using only primary official data from national statistics offices, finance ministries, and international organisations.</p>
    <div class="lang-switch"><a href="/faq/immigration-statistics-comparison/">🌐 日本語版</a></div>
  </div>

  <section>
    <h2>Key comparisons by theme (latest official data)</h2>

    <h3>Fiscal impact</h3>
    <table>
      <thead>
        <tr><th>Country</th><th>Net fiscal balance</th><th>Scope</th><th>Source</th></tr>
      </thead>
      <tbody>
        <tr><td>🇩🇰 Denmark</td><td>−DKK 16bn/year</td><td>All immigrants &amp; descendants</td><td>Finansministeriet 2023</td></tr>
        <tr><td>🇳🇴 Norway</td><td>−NOK 4.1m/person (R3)</td><td>Asylum &amp; non-European family migration (NPV)</td><td>SSB / Holmøy &amp; Strøm 2017</td></tr>
        <tr><td>🇩🇪 Germany</td><td>−€2.1bn/year</td><td>2015 refugee cohort</td><td>Ifo Institut 2023</td></tr>
        <tr><td>🇸🇪 Sweden</td><td>+SEK 6bn/year (contribution)</td><td>Labour migrants only</td><td>Konjunkturinstitutet 2020</td></tr>
      </tbody>
    </table>

    <h3>Population share (definition varies by country)</h3>
    <table>
      <thead>
        <tr><th>Country</th><th>Share</th><th>Definition used</th></tr>
      </thead>
      <tbody>
        <tr><td>🇦🇺 Australia</td><td>~32%</td><td>Foreign-born (ABS 2024)</td></tr>
        <tr><td>🇨🇭 Switzerland</td><td>27.7%</td><td>Foreign nationals (OFS 2023)</td></tr>
        <tr><td>🇩🇪 Germany</td><td>25.6%</td><td>Migration background, broad definition (Destatis 2023)</td></tr>
        <tr><td>🇸🇪 Sweden</td><td>21%</td><td>Foreign-born (SCB 2024)</td></tr>
        <tr><td>🇧🇪 Belgium</td><td>13.8%*</td><td>Non-Belgian nationals (Statbel 2026). Foreign-origin incl. naturalised: 36.6%</td></tr>
        <tr><td>🇫🇷 France</td><td>11.3%</td><td>Foreign nationals (INSEE 2023)</td></tr>
      </tbody>
    </table>

    <h3>PISA 2022 mathematics gap (after ESCS socioeconomic control)</h3>
    <table>
      <thead>
        <tr><th>Country</th><th>Adjusted gap</th><th>Direction</th></tr>
      </thead>
      <tbody>
        <tr><td>🇫🇮 Finland</td><td>−42 pts</td><td>Native-born outperform immigrants</td></tr>
        <tr><td>🇸🇪 Sweden</td><td>−34 pts</td><td>Native-born outperform immigrants</td></tr>
        <tr><td>🇦🇺 Australia</td><td>+26 pts</td><td>Immigrants outperform native-born</td></tr>
        <tr><td>🇳🇿 New Zealand</td><td>+16 pts</td><td>Immigrants outperform native-born</td></tr>
      </tbody>
    </table>

    <h3>Crime statistics (suspect rate ratio, unadjusted)</h3>
    <table>
      <thead>
        <tr><th>Country</th><th>Ratio</th><th>Measure &amp; source</th></tr>
      </thead>
      <tbody>
        <tr><td>🇩🇪 Germany</td><td>3.7×</td><td>Non-German vs. German nationals (BKA PKS 2023)</td></tr>
        <tr><td>🇩🇰 Denmark</td><td>2.6× (age-adjusted)</td><td>Immigrants &amp; descendants vs. Danish-origin (DST)</td></tr>
        <tr><td>🇸🇪 Sweden</td><td>~2.5×</td><td>Immigrant background vs. native-born (BRÅ 2021)</td></tr>
        <tr><td>🇺🇸 United States</td><td>No federal cross-tabulation</td><td>FBI UCR / BJS — immigration status not collected</td></tr>
      </tbody>
    </table>
  </section>

  <section>
    <h2>What to watch when comparing across countries</h2>
    <ul>
      <li><strong>Definitions vary:</strong> "Immigrant" means foreign-born in some countries, foreign national in others, migration background (including 2nd generation) in Germany. The same percentage figure is not the same population.</li>
      <li><strong>Fiscal methodologies:</strong> Static vs. dynamic models, national vs. federal scope, included benefit categories — all differ. You cannot add or directly compare fiscal figures across countries.</li>
      <li><strong>Crime figures are unadjusted raw rates</strong> that do not control for age, sex, urban concentration, or socioeconomic status. They do not isolate the effect of immigrant origin per se.</li>
    </ul>
  </section>

